<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="timeline">The Timeline of Your Wedding Day Music</h2>

<p>It's your day, let's make it special. During your wedding day, there will be a few distinct parts that will require music, planning, and coordination.</p>

<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Ceremony</h3>

<p>The ceremony is magical. No matter how many times you witness one, you're bound to get the chills and feel emotional. For a perfect execution, here's what to consider.&nbsp;</p>

<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Before the Ceremony: </strong>Play soft music about 30 minutes before the start, as the guests are arriving and taking their seats. Once the ceremony is ready to begin, an announcement will likely be made for guests to take their seats.</li>
<li><strong>Wedding Procession: </strong>The arrival of the groom, family, ring bearer, and flower girls can each all walk down the aisle to one song. A different song should be played for the arrival of the bride, highlighting their unique entrance.</li>
<li><strong>During the Ceremony:</strong> You'll want to have a quality microphone for the officiant. It's a good idea to practice with the officiant for the moments when they'll need to turn the mic to the couple to give their vows.</li>
<li><strong>After the Ceremony:</strong> Choose a powerful and exciting song for the couple to walk off together after the ceremony.</li>
</ul>

<p>To put all of this together, you'll need a good sound technician to control the volume, make the transitions at the right moments, and prevent any issues like microphone feedback or volume being too low for guests to hear.</p>

<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Cocktail Hour</h3>

<p>Following the ceremony, most weddings move to the cocktail hour, where guests can grab a drink, some appetizers, and socialize before they move into the dinner venue. For the bride, groom and family, this is often the time for photos.</p>

<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Type of Music:</strong> The music during the cocktail hour is passive and sets the mood for the night. The volume should be medium since it&#8217;s not the main focus. You could hire an instrumental musician, or you could make a playlist for our DJ to play.</li>
<li><strong>End of the Cocktail Hour: </strong>Towards the end of the hour, an announcement can be made to ask people to take their seats at dinner.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Dinner &amp; Toasts</h3>

<p>During dinner the music is once again in the background with the volume at a low to medium level. Keep in mind the music will often be interrupted by other activities.</p>

<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Introducing the Wedding Party: </strong>Before dinner, the wedding party is typically introduced. Pick one song for their entrance, and make sure all names are clearly spelled out on your wedding timeline so that they are easy to read and pronounce.</li>
<li><strong>Toasts: </strong>Giving toasts<strong> </strong>requires special attention. They almost always go longer than expected, so you should plan for an additional 30 minutes. Since most people aren't public speakers, help prepare them by sending a few tips and maybe a short YouTube video with best practices. This can make a big difference!</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Dancing</h3>

<p>During the dancing portion of the evening, the music moves into the forefront. The volume goes up; there are fewer interruptions, if any; and people are on the dance floor having a good time.</p>

<p><strong>Dancing is the time for your DJ to shine</strong>, and if you've chosen the right one, they'll bring their A game on your special evening. Hopefully you're giving them the autonomy to do their best work – from there the only thing left to do is to have fun, enjoy yourself, and dance the night away.</p>

